CH.01 — The Platform

Edge is an output device.
You supply the signal.

Most biofeedback research delivers feedback through screens — a line graph, a colored bar, a waveform the athlete has to watch. That visual demand competes with the very task being trained. The screen is not incidental to the problem; it is the problem.

Edge receives your physiological data stream — HRV from a Polar H10, EEG from Muse S Athena, EMG from any BLE-enabled sensor — and translates it into real-time lens tint modulation. The athlete never looks at anything. The feedback reaches them through their visual field without interrupting it.

Your IRB, your population, your research question — Edge is the missing instrument.

CH.02 — Compatible Inputs

Bring your sensors.
Edge handles the rest.

Output-layer agnostic. If your lab has a validated sensor protocol, Edge slots in as the feedback delivery layer without replacing your measurement infrastructure.

Live
HRV

Current implementation via Polar H10 (RR interval). Supports resonance frequency training, coherence-based biofeedback, and autonomic state feedback. Works in every session, not just lab visits.

Live
HRV Coherence

Psychophysiological coherence derived from HRV. Continuous ambient feedback during resonance frequency training — no screen required, no session interruption. Feedback through the visual field, not competing with it.

In Progress
EEG

Muse S Athena integration in active development. Alpha and SMR neurofeedback during actual sport practice — the missing feedback layer for ecologically valid EEG neurofeedback protocols.

Open Protocol
EMG

If your lab has an EMG sensor and a muscle activation algorithm, Edge receives the output signal directly over BLE. Your processing, your thresholds — Edge delivers the feedback. No re-instrumenting your existing setup.

Open Platform
Any BLE

Edge accepts any physiological stream via a simple GATT write protocol — GSR, respiration, force plate output, proprietary wearables. Single uint8 byte, open documentation, no lock-in. If it transmits over BLE, it feeds Edge.

CH.03 — Proof of Concept
4/5
Children off ADHD medication

In clinical pilots using the predecessor Narbis neurofeedback device — integrated EEG smart glasses with active lens-based feedback — 4 of 5 children discontinued ADHD medication in as few as 20 training sessions.

// Note on evidence status — methods disclosure

These results are from clinical pilots using Narbis's predecessor device, not Edge. They have not been published in a peer-reviewed journal. They demonstrate that lens-based biofeedback delivery produces behavioral outcomes — proof-of-concept for the delivery mechanism Edge extends to any physiological input. We include this with full context because the researchers we want to work with will ask, and they should. The opportunity is to be first to publish on this modality.

// From clinical attention training to sport performance — the open question

The predecessor data comes from clinical attention training in children. The same principle — real-time, ambient, lens-based feedback driving measurable behavioral adaptation — applies directly to motor learning, coordination, and sport-specific performance contexts. That connection has not been published. The question of whether state-contingent feedback delivered through the visual field during actual performance produces durable coordination changes is precisely what labs with validated EMG, HRV, and force protocols are positioned to answer. Edge exists to make those studies possible.

CH.04b — Lens Variants

Two feedback signatures.
Same open platform.

Both lenses respond to the same BLE signal. The choice between them is a research design decision — high-contrast feedback vs. subtle chromatic shift — not a hardware change.

Variant A
Gray / Clear
PC · single-cell · bendable

Lenses transition from clear (35% T) to deeply tinted (8% T) — the same optical shift as putting on dark sunglasses. High-contrast, unambiguous feedback. The athlete knows when the lenses are dark. Suited for protocols requiring strong, salient feedback signals where subtlety isn't the goal.

Live — driven by simulated HRV coherence
Clear = coherent · high RMSSD 35%
Clear transmissivity35%
Max attenuation8%
Delta T27 percentage points
Steps256 (perceptible: 30–255)
ConstructionPC · single-cell · bendable
Best for: high-arousal sport contexts, protocols requiring unambiguous feedback, attention training, broad-population studies where subtle cues may be missed.
Variant B
Yellow / Clear
PC · single-cell · bendable

Lenses shift from optically clear (84% T) to a subtle warm yellow tint (79% T) — a 5-point transmissivity change that registers as a chromatic shift rather than a brightness change. Low-distraction, low-salience feedback. The athlete perceives a warm color cast, not darkness. Suited for protocols where maintaining undisrupted visual performance is critical.

// Research context
Yellow lens literature spans Irlen spectral filtering (ADHD/dyslexia), blue-blocking/circadian work (Carroll, Toronto), and sport contrast enhancement. All prior studies used static tints. Dynamic state-contingent modulation is the open question.
CH.05 — Feedback Modes

Three ways
to close the loop.

01
Continuous Modulation

Lens opacity tracks physiological state in real time — darkening as arousal or incoherence increases, clearing as the athlete returns to target state. Continuous, ambient, non-interruptive. For sustained training protocols where session continuity matters.

02
Breathing Pacing

Lenses cycle through opacity values synchronized to a target breathing rhythm — typically 4–6 breaths per minute for HRV resonance protocols. Visual pacing without a screen. Can run standalone or coupled with biofeedback signal for combined pacing and state feedback.

03
Audio-Visual Entrainment

Strobe mode at defined frequencies, optionally paired with binaural beats for photic and auditory stimulation protocols. Configurable frequency range. For research applications in neural entrainment and cognitive state modulation.

CH.06 — Signal Lineage

Official NASA Spinoff.
25 years in the signal chain.

In the 1990s, Dr. Alan Pope at NASA's Langley Research Center invented the engagement index — dividing beta brainwave power by combined alpha and theta output to produce a real-time attention score from 1 to 6. It was built to solve a specific problem: as cockpit automation increased, pilots were becoming dangerously disengaged. Dr. Pope's system gave them a way to train their own attention the same way they trained their reflexes.

"We brought the training into real life. You're getting feedback while doing things you've got to do anyway." — Devon Greco, NASA Spinoff feature

Around 2000, Devon Greco, his father Dr. Domenic Greco, and his mother Lindsay Greco exclusively licensed NASA's engagement index and founded CyberLearning Technologies. Their SMART BrainGames platform (2003) was an official NASA Spinoff — the first universal system to use video games as the neurofeedback delivery mechanism, with game difficulty responding in real time to the user's own brainwaves. Dr. Alan Pope served as advisor to both CyberLearning and Narbis.

The smart glasses concept has a specific origin. As Dr. Domenic Greco lost muscle control to ALS, Devon built him eye-tracking glasses so he could still communicate using his gaze. That hands-on work with wearable gaze hardware led directly to the idea: take the neurofeedback signal off the screen entirely and deliver it through lenses the user wears during any real-world activity — turning the feedback ambient, continuous, and ecological. Devon founded Narbis in 2013 to build it, carrying forward the methodology and IP lineage from CyberLearning's official NASA Spinoff work ↗.
